<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>🏠 Builder Basics — The Sloped Roof (Extension · Beginner)</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Variables · <strong>Course:</strong> Builder Basics · <strong>Type:</strong> Extension Activity · <strong>Level:</strong> Beginner · <strong>Time:</strong> about 30 minutes</p>
<blockquote>
<p>🧩 This is a bonus challenge, not a weekly lesson. Try it once you are happy building with loops.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Open the <strong>Sloped Roof</strong> world but do not run it yet. Here is what the program does.</p>
<p>It builds a roof out of stairs, one square <strong>ring</strong> at a time. A ring is a square outline — like the edge of a picture frame. The program builds the first ring, then builds another ring <strong>on top</strong> of it, then another, then another. Four rings in total, stacked up.</p>
<p>Here is the clever part: each ring is <strong>shorter</strong> than the one below it. A number called <code>roof_len</code> decides how long each side of a ring is. It starts at 7. After every ring it loses 2. So the rings get smaller and higher as they go up, and they step up toward a single block at the very top — the peak.</p>
<p><strong>What shape does this make? Circle one:</strong> flat square · stepped pyramid roof · single line</p>
<p><strong>Why is each ring smaller than the ring below it?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Watch the Variable Change 🔢</h2>
<p>A <strong>variable</strong> is a name that holds a number. The special thing about a variable is that the number can <strong>change</strong> while the program runs.</p>
<p>In this program the variable is called <code>roof_len</code>. It holds how long each side of the ring is. It starts at 7, and after each ring it loses 2.</p>
<p>Fill in the table. The first one is done for you.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Layer</th>
<th><code>roof_len</code> =</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Layer 1 (bottom)</td>
<td>7</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Layer 2</td>
<td>____</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Layer 3</td>
<td>____</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Layer 4 (top)</td>
<td>____</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>The widest ring is at the</strong> (circle one)<strong>:</strong> bottom · top</p>
<hr />
<h2>3 · Think It Through ✏️</h2>
<p>No building yet — just thinking.</p>
<p><strong>The variable <code>roof_len</code> loses 2 after each ring. Imagine it did NOT change and stayed 7 the whole time. What would the roof look like then?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Which number would you change to make the roof start out wider at the bottom?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Build It 📸</h2>
<p>Now run it for real.</p>
<ol>
<li>Open the <strong>Sloped Roof</strong> world.</li>
<li>Type <strong><code>slope</code></strong> in the Minecraft chat and press enter to run the program.</li>
<li>Watch the rings build up, getting smaller each time, until they reach the peak.</li>
</ol>
<p>Then change the starting number. Make <code>roof_len</code> start at <strong>9</strong> instead of 7, run it again, and see how the roof changes.</p>
<p>Send a photo or video of your roof, then explain it. Use these starters — write 2 or 3 sentences.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>My variable <code>roof_len</code> started at … and lost 2 each time, so …</p>
<p>The roof steps up to a point because the variable …</p>
<p>When I changed the starting number to 9, the roof …</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h3>Submit ✅</h3>
<p>Send this worksheet + a photo or video of your sloped roof to teacher on KakaoTalk.</p>
